{{Constitutions of Poland}}
{{expand language|topic=|langcode=pl|otherarticle=Konstytucja marcowa|date=March 2015}}
The [[Second Polish Republic]] adopted the '''March Constitution''' on 17 March 1921, after ousting the occupation of the [[Germany|German]]/[[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussian]] forces in the 1918 [[Greater Poland Uprising (1918–1919)|Greater Poland Uprising]], and avoiding conquest by the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]]s in the 1920 [[Polish-Soviet War]]. The Constitution, based on the French one{{clarify|date=September 2016}}<!-- which one? -->, was regarded as very democratic. Among others, it expressly ruled out discrimination on racial or religious grounds.<ref>[[Niall Ferguson]], The War of the World, The Penguin Press, New York 2006, page 271</ref> It also abolished all  [[royal title]]s and state privileges, and banned the use of [[blazon]]s.

It was partially adjusted by the 1926 [[August Novelization]], and superseded by the [[Polish Constitution of 1935]] (April Constitution).

